## The subject matter of logic

In propositional logic, we take the proposition as primitive and do not subject it to further analysis. For instance, we translate "Alex walks and Brianna walks" simply as $p\wedge q$, with the key

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $p$ = Anthony walks </p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $q$ = Briana walks </p>

In predicate logic, we subject these small propositions to further analysis. In fact, later we will analyze "Alex walks and Brianna walks" as $Wa\wedge Wb$ where

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $a$ = Anthony </p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $b$ = Briana </p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $Wx$ = $x$ walks </p>

The first to propose something like this was Aristotle in his *Prior Analytics*. He described propositions as follows in Book I, Chapter 1 of the *Prior Analytics* (from [this edition](https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Aristotle%202014%20-%20Prior%20Analytics%20Book%20I%20Chapters%201-12.pdf)):

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Aristotle%202014%20-%20Prior%20Analytics%20Book%20I%20Chapters%201-12%20prop-v2.png" alt="Aristotle on propositions" width="700"/>

As we can see here, he thought that the primary subject-matter of logic was statements like:

- "Every human walks", which is a universal statement, ascribing walking (or the ability to walk) to all humans.
- "Some animals walk," which is a particular statement, ascribing walking (or the ability to walk) to some animals.
- "Animals talk," which is what Aristotle calls an indefinite statement, which is "without a mark" as to whether it is universal or particular

When Aristotle says that a proposition affirms "something of something," he is thinking about examples like these. The starkest contrast to propositional logic *per se* is that in these examples we are given some further sense of what makes the basic propositions true or false: it is the relation between the subject (human, animal) and the predicate (walk, talk). This idea is retained in contemporary predicate logic. Part of what we will learn in this course is the ways in which contemporary predicate logic goes beyond Aristotelian logic, but it is safe to say that the relation between a subject and a predicate features crucially in both.

The other important notion that Aristotle introduces in Book I, Chapter 1 is that of "deduction," or what we might today call "consequence" or "logical consequence":

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Aristotle%202014%20-%20Prior%20Analytics%20Book%20I%20Chapters%201-12%20deduction-v2.png" alt="Aristotle on deduction" width="700"/>

This general idea is probably familiar from your first logic course, where we say that a *valid argument* is an argument whose premises guarantee the truth of its conclusion. In the quotation, what we today call "valid argument" is what Aristotle calls "deduction," and what we today call "premises" are what Aristotle calls "certain things being stated," and finally what we call the "conclusion" is what Aristotle calls that which "follows of necessity."

Part of what we strive to do in our first logic course is specify the sense in which the conclusion follows of necessity from the premises. One way we do that in the propositional setting is with truth-tables: any row of the table is such that if all the premises are true, the conclusion is true. Another way we do that in the propositional setting is with proofs: we can get from the premises to the conclusion using only certain specified rules. For instance, using either of these methods we can show that the argument with premise $p\wedge q$ and conclusion $p$ is a valid argument. Aristotle in these passage of the *Prior Analytics* does try to specify the sense of necessity he had in mind using cognate-notions like "because" and "by." Perhaps the clearest way he specifies the sense of necessity is by all the examples of valid arguments (or deductions) which he gives. And perhaps that is ultimately what the "certain specified rules" we use when we produce proofs come down to: paradigmatic examples of valid arguments.

<br>

## Conversions and valid arguments

Aristotle opens Book I, Chapter 2 of *Prior Analytics* with what he calls "conversions." These are one-premise arguments where the subject and predicates are interchanged between the sole premise and the conclusion of the argument.[^1] Here are the general forms and the examples which Aristotle gives:

[^1]: Perhaps they don't even justify, in Aristotle's eyes, the title of a "deduction," since it is not always obvious they satisfy the constraint from the last quotation in [The subject matter of logic](#the-subject-matter-of-logic) section that the conclusion be different than the conclusion.

<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Name</th>
    <th>Valid argument</th>
    <th>Example</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>First Conversion</td>
    <td>Some F are G $\vdash$ Some G are F</td>
    <td>Some pleasures are good $\vdash$ Some good is pleasurable</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Second Conversion</td>
    <td>No F are G $\vdash$ No G are F</td>
    <td>No pleasures are good $\vdash$ No good is pleasurable</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Third Conversion</td>
    <td>No F are G $\vdash$ All F are not G</td>
    <td>No pleasures are good $\vdash$ All pleasures are not good</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
In this, we use the $\vdash$ of contemporary logic to separate out the premise on the left from the conclusion on the right. Recall that $\vdash$ is the *consequence relation* which one can pronounce out loud as "therefore" or "hence" or "has as a consequence" or "entails."

## Non-conversions and invalid arguments

He also produces an example of an argument showing a situation in which one cannot interchange the subject and predicate:
<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Invalid argument</th>
    <th>Example</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Some F is not G $\nvdash$ Some G is not F</td>
    <td>Some animal is not man $\nvdash$ Some man is not an animal</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
The argument is invalid simply because "Some animal is not man" is true while "Some man is not an animal" is false. In contemporary terms, valid arguments have the feature that if all the premises are true, then the conclusion is true. To use Aristotle's language, from the statement "Some animal is not man" being so it simply does not necessarily follow that "Some man is not an animal".

<br>

## Conversions and existential import

The contemporary predicate logic which we will study in this course agrees with Aristotle on the validity and invalidity of these examples. However, Aristotle produces another example of what he take to be a valid argument which is judged to be invalid by the lights of contemporary logic:

<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Name</th>
    <th>Valid argument</th>
    <th>Example</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Fourth Conversion</td>
    <td>All F are G $\vdash$ Some G are F</td>
    <td>All pleasure is good $\vdash$ Some good is pleasurable</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>

Aristotle thinks that this is a valid argument, and his example and related examples indeed are highly suggestive of its validity. This valid argument is sometimes described as the view that universal statements have "existential import" since the "existential" is another way of describing statements we form with "some." The contemporary logic that we will learn agrees that these arguments are valid *when you already know in advance that there are things that are F's*. Hence, the one place where the argument is thought to be invalid by today's lights is in the case where there are no F's. This might seem like a degenerate case in some sense, a case that would not be of much interest. However, the long story short is that countenancing examples of arguments where the subjects and predicates can be uninstantiated is a useful simplifying assumption, much akin to countenancing the number zero in arithmetic. Even if there are no collections of zero things that we count, we are all familiar with the idea that the rules of addition and subtraction are made easier if there is a number zero available. Likewise, it turns out that some of the rules of predicate logic will be easier to state and use if we allow there to be properties which are uninstantiated.

<br>

## The first figure

The arguments discussed so far pertain to a single pair of a subject and predicate F and G. The next valid arguments that Aristotle identified in Book 1, Chapter 4 of the *Prior Analytics* pertain to a triple F,G,H. Each of these valid arguments has two premises, in which one of the three of F,G,H appears in both of the premises. The four valid arguments that Aristotle identified have traditional names attached to them. In Latin these traditional names were helpful mnemonics for the arguments which helped students memorize the argument patterns. The presence of names conveys the extent to which Aristotle's logic constituted the core of logic for many centuries. The four arguments collectively are called the "first figure":[^2]

[^2]: There is some evidence that this grouping had something to do with a diagrammatic representation of the arguments, hence the term "figure."

<table style="width:120%">
  <tr>
    <th>Traditional Name</th>
    <th>Valid argument</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Barbara</td>
    <td>All F are G, All G are H $\vdash$ All F are H</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Celarent</td>
    <td>No F are G, All H are F $\vdash$ No H are G</td>
  <tr>
    <td>Darii</td>
    <td>All F are G, Some H are F $\vdash$ Some H are G</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Ferio</td>
    <td>No F are G, Some H are F $\vdash$ Some H are not G</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<br>

For our purposes, it is not important that we memorize the traditional names of the valid arguments. But it is useful to have them for ease of reference. In homework and exam contexts, we will always provide the tables like above.

Recall that in valid arguments, it does not matter in which order you list the premises. Hence, we would also say that the following argument is an example of Barbara: All G are H, All F are G $\vdash$ All F are H.

It is important in logic to become good at recognizing when an example is an example of one of these abstract argument forms. That is what these simple multiple choice questions are asking one to do:

<br>


*Example 1*

Consider the following argument: All French-majors are generous, Some hockey-players are French-majors $\vdash$ Some hockey-players are generous. Which of the four valid arguments is this an example of?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is it?
| Barbara
| Celarent
| *Darii
| Ferio
```

<br>

*Example 2*

Consider the following argument: No French-majors are grumpy, Some hockey-players are French players $\vdash$ Some hockey-players are not grumpy.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is it?
| Barbara
| Celarent
| Darii
| *Ferio
```

<br>

Experience suggests that answering questions like this becomes more challenging if there is no association between the initial letter of the English subjects and predicates and the valid arguments.

*Example 3*

Consider the following argument: No one living in LA is living in Montreal, All people living in Westwood are living in LA $\vdash$ No one living in Westwood is living in Montreal.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is it?
| Barbara
| *Celarent
| Darii
| Ferio
```

To help one do this kind of pattern-matching, it can be useful to write on top of the sentences the letters F,G,H that feature in our statement of the four validities up above.

<br>

One way to make the idea of pattern-matching more precise is with substitutions, which we use frequently in logic.


*Example 4*

Consider the following argument: No A are B, Some C are A $\vdash$ Some C are not B.

Replace A by F and replace B by G, and replace C by H. What argument do you get?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is it?
| Barbara
| Celarent
| Darii
| *Ferio
```

<br>

*Example 5*

Consider the following argument: All B are C, Some A are B $\vdash$ Some A are C

Replace B by F and replace C by G, and replace A by H. What argument do you get?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is it?
| Barbara
| Celarent
| *Darii
| Ferio
```

<br>

We say that one abstract argument is a *substitution-instance* of another if it can be obtained via a replacement like the ones we have done up above. As we go along in our study of logic, it will be important that we practice lots with recognizing substitution-instances. Here are two simple examples:

*Example 6*

Consider the following argument: All I are J, All J are K $\vdash$ All I are K. Which argument is this a substitution-instance of?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is it?
| *Barbara
| Celarent
| Darii
| Ferio
```

<br>

*Example 7*

Consider the following argument: No P are Q, All R are P $\vdash$ No R are Q. Which argument is this a substitution-instance of?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is it?
| Barbara
| *Celarent
| Darii
| Ferio
```

<br>

In addition to learning about the origins and history of logic as a subject, reviewing these four traditional Aristotelian syllogisms is a useful way to practice with the key concepts of replacement and substitution that are important throughout logic.

