## The second figure

In Book 1, Chapter 5 of the *Prior Analytics* Aristotle identified another four pairs of valid arguments, which bear the following traditional names and collectively are called the "second figure":

<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Traditional Name</th>
    <th>Valid argument</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Cesare</td>
    <td>No A are B, All C are B $\vdash$ No C are A</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Camestres</td>
    <td>All A are B, No C are B $\vdash$ No C are A</td>
  <tr>
    <td>Festino</td>
    <td>No A are B, Some C are B $\vdash$ Some C are not A</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Baroco</td>
    <td>All A are B, Some C are not B $\vdash$ Some C are not A</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<br>

Aristotle then proceeds to show how to *derive* these valid arguments from the valid arguments in the first figure together with the conversions. This is the prototype of the derivations that we do in contemporary logic. We will spend a lot of time later learning a deductive system for predicate logic; for the moment, we simply describe the arguments as Aristotle presents them.

<br>

*Example 8*.

Proof of Cesare: No A are B, All C are B $\vdash$ No C

1. No A are B &nbsp; :assumption
2. All C are B &nbsp; :assumption
3. No B are A &nbsp; :Second Conversion, 1.
4. No C are A &nbsp; :Celarent 3,2

